Goal

Improve the QuickStart so it is not just comparing model answers, but evaluating the whole RAG pipeline in a more structured, reproducible, and trustworthy way.

That means making each evaluation run clearly capture:

what was asked
what the system considers true
what evidence was retrieved
what each model answered
how each answer was scored
why one passed or failed
Step-by-step plan
Step 1 — Define the target evaluation architecture

Goal: align on the structure before changing code.

What to do

Define the QuickStart around four core artifacts:

run.json
truth.json
model_output.json
score.json
Why

Right now, parts of this already exist implicitly in your flow, but not as explicit first-class artifacts. Making them explicit will make the system easier to reason about, debug, compare, and extend.

Deliverable

A short architecture note or ADR describing:

what each artifact contains
when it is created
how it is used in evaluation
Step 2 — Turn “truth” into a first-class saved object

Goal: make truth structured, visible, and reusable.

What to do

For every generated evaluation question, save a structured truth object instead of relying only on a generated expected_answer.

truth.json should include
question
expected_answer
required_concepts
required_documents
expected_chunks or supporting chunk ids
abstention_expected
forbidden_claims (later if needed)
truth_generation_metadata
source docs used
model used to generate truth
timestamp
version
Why

Today, the concepts are effectively derived and reused within a comparison, which is good, but they should be persisted and frozen so the same question can be re-run later and still be evaluated against the same truth.

Deliverable

A structured truth schema and persistence layer support for storing it with the synthesized question set.

Step 3 — Freeze truth at question-set creation time

Goal: separate setup from evaluation.

What to do

Change the flow so truth is generated once when the question set is created, not re-derived during scoring.

Desired flow
user uploads documents
system generates questions
system generates structured truth for each question
truth is saved
model comparisons use that saved truth
Why

This is the biggest harness-style improvement. It keeps your system flexible and dynamic, while still making evaluation reproducible.

Deliverable

Updated question generation flow so each generated question has a saved truth payload attached to it.

Step 4 — Split retrieval truth from answer truth

Goal: evaluate retrieval and generation separately.

What to do

Add two layers of expected truth:

Retrieval truth
which documents should ideally support the question
which chunks are relevant
whether key source material was retrieved
Answer truth
which concepts must be covered
whether abstention is expected
whether unsupported claims are forbidden
Why

This helps you answer:

Did the model fail because retrieval missed the right evidence?
Or did retrieval succeed and the model still answered poorly?

That distinction is very important for improving the system.

Deliverable

Two separate scoring inputs:

retrieval truth
answer truth
Step 5 — Move more evaluation into deterministic checks

Goal: reduce over-reliance on LLM-as-judge.

What to do

Add deterministic validators for things that do not need a judge model.

Examples
missing required concepts
missing required documents
answer mentions unsupported facts
answer fails to abstain when context is insufficient
answer references sources not retrieved
answer misses required citations
answer contains forbidden claims
Why

These checks are more stable, explainable, and easier to debug than purely judge-based scoring.

Deliverable

A deterministic evaluation layer that runs before or alongside the judge model.

Step 6 — Keep the judge, but narrow its role

Goal: use the judge where it adds the most value.

What to do

Use the LLM judge for:

completeness nuance
reasoning quality
regulatory correctness
whether the answer is responsive and appropriately cautious

Do not rely on the judge for checks that can be made rule-based.

Why

This gives you a more reliable evaluation stack:

deterministic checks for objective conditions
LLM judge for nuanced interpretation
Deliverable

Clear separation of:

rule-based checks
judge-based checks
Step 7 — Make the profile contract machine-enforced

Goal: turn profile guidance into actual evaluation logic.

What to do

Take the important FSI/compliance rules from your profile and enforce them in scoring/verdict logic.

Examples
do not invent thresholds or legal requirements
distinguish explicit requirement from interpretation
abstain when support is insufficient
cite supporting evidence when making a claim
Why

Right now these rules are useful as guidance, but they become much more valuable when they affect pass/fail and model comparison.

Deliverable

Profile-driven validators tied directly to verdict logic.

Step 8 — Save a full artifact for each model run

Goal: make each comparison replayable and auditable.

What to do

For each run, save:

run.json
run id
question id
profile id
dataset/corpus version
retrieval settings
prompt version
model names
judge model
timestamp
model_output.json

For each model:

answer text
retrieved docs
retrieved chunks
citations
latency
token counts
maybe decomposition queries / retrieval metadata
score.json
deterministic check results
judge scores
per-dimension scores
fail reasons
verdict
winner
Why

This makes your QuickStart much closer to a real evaluation framework and gives you a strong foundation for regression testing later.

Deliverable

Artifact creation pipeline for each evaluation run.

Step 9 — Add pass/fail gates, not just a winner

Goal: stop “good-looking but wrong” answers from winning.

What to do

Introduce gates such as:

Retrieval gate: required evidence not retrieved
Grounding gate: claims unsupported by retrieved evidence
Completeness gate: core required concepts missing
Safety/compliance gate: unsupported regulatory guidance
Abstention gate: should have abstained but didn’t
Why

This makes evaluation much more trustworthy. Sometimes neither model should win.

Deliverable

Verdict logic that supports:

pass
fail
winner if applicable
fail reasons
Step 10 — Improve synthesis so generated truth is better grounded

Goal: make auto-generated questions/truth less biased.

What to do

Improve question synthesis so it samples supporting material more intentionally across the uploaded corpus.

Instead of
relying too much on the first portion of available chunks
Move toward
document-balanced selection
section diversity
better source coverage
explicit support links between truth and source chunks
Why

If truth is generated from a narrow slice of the corpus, evaluation will also be narrow.

Deliverable

More balanced truth generation inputs and stronger traceability from truth back to source docs.

Step 11 — Improve coverage checking

Goal: make “missing concept” analysis more reliable.

What to do

Keep your current concept-based coverage, but plan to improve it over time.

Near-term
use persisted required_concepts
improve simple matching rules
map concepts to supporting chunks
Later
add embedding-based concept matching
or judge-assisted concept grounding for hard cases
Why

This makes “Model B missed X” much more credible and easier to explain in UI.

Deliverable

A stronger concept coverage pipeline tied to saved truth objects.

Step 12 — Surface truth and evidence in the UI

Goal: make the evaluation explainable to users.

What to do

Update the UI so users can see:

question
expected truth
required concepts
required docs
retrieved evidence by model
covered vs missing concepts
judge reasoning
final verdict
Why

This is where the architecture becomes useful to people, not just to the backend.

Deliverable

A comparison screen that shows not just answers, but also:

what should have been found
what was retrieved
what was missed
why the verdict happened
Step 13 — Add scenario/version tracking

Goal: make experiments comparable across time.

What to do

Version:

truth schema
question set
corpus
profile
prompts
retrieval strategy
Why

Then you can answer:

did the new retrieval improve completeness?
did prompt changes reduce hallucinations?
did a new judge make scoring stricter?
Deliverable

Basic version fields in run artifacts and stored records.

Step 14 — Add experiment tracking later

Goal: support regression analysis over time.

What to do

Once artifacts are stable, add experiment tracking for:

model vs model comparisons
retrieval config changes
prompt revisions
profile tuning
Why

This is how the QuickStart starts to feel like a benchmark harness rather than a one-off demo.

Deliverable

A lightweight experiment history view or tracking backend.

Suggested implementation phases
Phase 1 — Foundation

Do these first:

define artifact structure
create structured truth.json
freeze truth at question generation time
stop recomputing concepts during scoring
save required concepts and expected evidence
Phase 2 — Stronger evaluation

Then:
6. split retrieval truth from answer truth
7. add deterministic checks
8. enforce profile contract rules
9. add pass/fail gates

Phase 3 — Better UX and reproducibility

Then:
