🧠 Key shift (important)

Instead of thinking:

Model A vs Model B

You move to:

A set of model runs, each with results, and comparisons are derived from that set

✅ How to structure it properly
1. Each run = multiple model evaluations

A single evaluation run should look like:

{
  "run_id": "run-123",
  "question_id": "q-456",
  "models": [
    "qwen3-14b",
    "llama-scout-17b",
    "mistral-24b"
  ]
}

2. Store results per model (NOT A/B)

Instead of:

model_a_output.json
model_b_output.json

You store:

model_outputs.json
{
  "run_id": "run-123",
  "models": [
    {
      "model_id": "qwen3-14b",
      "output": {...},
      "retrieval": {...},
      "latency": 1200
    },
    {
      "model_id": "llama-scout-17b",
      "output": {...},
      "retrieval": {...},
      "latency": 900
    }
  ]
}
scores.json
{
  "run_id": "run-123",
  "scores": [
    {
      "model_id": "qwen3-14b",
      "completeness": 0.85,
      "groundedness": 0.9,
      "passed": true
    },
    {
      "model_id": "llama-scout-17b",
      "completeness": 0.7,
      "groundedness": 0.95,
      "passed": false
    }
  ]
}
🧩 Where comparison fits now

Comparison becomes a separate derived layer

Option A — Dynamic comparison (recommended)

You compute comparison on demand:

Examples:

pick best model
rank models
compare any subset
{
  "ranking": [
    "qwen3-14b",
    "mistral-24b",
    "llama-scout-17b"
  ]
}

👉 No need to store permanently

Option B — Store comparison snapshot

Optional:

{
  "run_id": "run-123",
  "comparison": {
    "winner": "qwen3-14b",
    "ranking": [...],
    "rules_version": "v2"
  }
}

👉 Useful for audit/history

🔥 Why this matters

Because:

Today (A/B mindset)
tightly coupled
not scalable
hard to extend
Future (multi-model mindset)
any number of models
easy ranking
reusable results
flexible comparison
🧠 What happens across runs?

You asked:

model A can be different per run — what happens then?

That’s totally fine because:

👉 Model identity is stored explicitly per run

Example:

Run 1
models = ["qwen3-14b", "llama"]
Run 2
models = ["mistral", "qwen3-14b"]

No problem because:

each run is independent
results are tied to model_id, not position
🧩 Important design rule

👉 Never rely on position (A, B, C)
👉 Always rely on model_id

📊 Bonus: cross-run comparisons

Once structured this way, you unlock:

Compare model across runs

Example:

how did qwen3-14b perform across 20 questions?
Aggregate scoring
{
  "model_id": "qwen3-14b",
  "avg_score": 0.87,
  "pass_rate": 0.9
}

👉 This is HUGE for your QuickStart value

🧠 Clean mental model
Instead of:
Run = A vs B
Think:
Run = Question + Truth + {Model Results}
Comparison = function(Model Results)
✅ Final recommendation
Store:
Required
run.json
truth.json
model_outputs.json (array per model)
scores.json (array per model)
Optional
comparison.json
Compute dynamically:
winner
ranking
filtered comparisons (A vs B vs C)
best model per metric
🔚 Bottom line
Models should be stored as a list, not A/B slots
Each model has its own independent result + score
Comparison is a derived layer
It can be stored, but should always be recomputable